segments.text: The objectives that you had in Moscow, new air routes into Moscow, development of free or exchange of weather information, and the shuttle bases, were they accomplished?
The exchange of weather information was by far the most successful, and some way or another,
whenever this Navy representative, the United States Navy representative came over they met him on time and were very cordial and this went well.
I wish everything else went that easy in relation to the Russians.
And we continued throughout the, until the end of the Japanese war to get all the weather information we needed from the Russians and very reliable.
That was successful.
The establishment of air routes wasn't too successful.
We never even approached getting an air route in the northern Murmask area down to Leningrad and Moscow.
Never even approached that.
They wouldn't even talk about it.
Why not, do you think?
I don't know.
Just wouldn't do it.
Weather-wise, it would have been a difficult one.

They just didn't want, on the question of air routes, they just did not want to open up their country that much and make it that easy for foreign airplanes and foreign air crews to fly over their country.
I'm sure this is a basic philosophy.
They just didn't want to do it.
It's opened up the country too much.
They didn't want that many foreigners in their country.
How about the southern routes?
The southern route from—see, we had at that time a United States Army organization in Iran called the Southern Supply Command, I think that's what it was.
Were they British?
Yeah.
And pouring Lend-Lease equipment, just pouring it up through the truck rail routes into southern Russia.
We weren't successful in establishing an air transport command route into Moscow at all.

Matter of fact, it was difficult enough even to establish the required air transport sorties up to the shuttle bases to resupply them with the necessary bombs, belly tanks, and maintenance equipment, and fuel.
Fuel, I don't think we had.
or they could provide the fuel.
But we weren't successful there.
Now, on the Alcib route.
Which one?
Alcib, from Alaska to Siberia, across into the European front.
See, that's the route that we flew a lot of the airplanes, actually flew the airplanes through.
They picked them up in Alaska.
We tried our best, and I personally wrote.
I figured I had the answer to it.
I wrote a personal study to General Dean, and the ambassador was very happy to get it, and even sent it forward to General Arnold, well, the Air Force back home.
And we all agreed it was a way to get the Russians to start building bases in Siberia that would take B-17s if we gave them to them.
And I think I even recommended giving them a few because it would force them to start building bases in Siberia
that would take bombers.
And then if they would build bases to take bombers, then we could ultimately, if necessary, use their bases to bomb Japan from the north.
Sure.
So it was sort of a leverage that we would do.
Well, they wanted the airplane.
So you wanted to fly from Alaska to Vladivostok?
Yeah.
And actually, that's the way they ferried fighter airplanes, a lot of them.
As a matter of fact, most of them.
Well, the P-39, most of them were assembled in Tehran and so on.

But we actually went as far as to, following my plan at Offord, we actually went as far as to organize a B-17 unit, which was going to be headed up by a very controversial old figure, Butch Morgan, a colonel in the Air Force, quite a character.
He actually made a visit over to Moscow, and we talked about it in detail.
But we didn't request Russian meetings at that time.
And we were going to organize a unit of B-17s, and he would fly the whole thing right through to get the B-17s in Russia.
Well, they went along with us until we got it up to Alaska.
Then they just stopped on the negotiation flat and said, well, look, we'll take the airplane.
They didn't want any aircraft.
And then as a result, we turned them down.
We didn't get any aircraft.
And that was my recommendation.
So they didn't want any American to land in Vladivostok?
That was the problem?
They didn't want any American flying into Russia, transporting aircraft.
Their fighter pilots came down to Tehran and picked up a P-39 and bombed into Russia.
We checked them out right there on the base in Tehran, and they flew into Russia.
Or they came to Alaska.
Or they came to Alaska and flew there.
And air transport-wise, there was never an air transport aircraft, an ATC airplane per se, that ever flew into Moscow from Murmansk, Alaska, or Tehran.
So that objective, in effect, we didn't achieve.
On the shuttle bases, as I've told you, we developed those.
And it turned out to be operational.
To what extent it impacted the end of the war, or accelerated the end of the war, slowed the fighting down, or impressed the Germans,
I'm not sure.
But it served to make us work closer with the Russians and vice versa.
It gave us more of an insight, let's say intelligence-wise, into the Red Army and the Red Air Force and their thinking, their war planning, operations.
By the same token, it gave them a better insight into our strategic bomber operations
and our people, our crews, our equipment.
I think from a standpoint of maybe impressing each other, it was successful.
From a standpoint of tactical applications and operations, the Red Army was advancing so far, so fast anyhow, into Germany from the east that
It wasn't really absolutely necessary.
I think it was more of a political strategic coordination plan than a tactical requirement.
I learned a lot from it, and my tour in Russia.
I wouldn't take anything in the world for that.
Yeah, let's talk about, sort of summarize your tour.
Is there any other specifics that we should talk about as far as your tour in Russia?
Before we summarize it, let me think a moment.
Maybe I ought to bring one thing up.
And if I'm not mistaken, I think I talked openly with the Ambassador, and certainly with General Dean about this several times, is the visits of vets, if you will, to Russia.
During a time we were over there, to see certain things like, I forget the name of the industrial giant, either General Motors or somebody that was brought on duty in OPA.
Office of Price Administration.
Right.
During the war, or no, production, some job in production.
It was some industrial titan that was brought on duty aboard
industrial planning, he came over to Russia.
It was the head of some big corporation, either General Motors or General Electric, something like that.
I forget who he was.
Anyhow, he knew General Ambassador Herman was a friend.
And, of course, he made arrangements for his visit to certain factories in Russia.
And Ambassador Harriman, of course, usually received these bips first, meets them, you know, depends on what their stature is and how much time he gives them, and who escorts them in the field.
I never escorted any of the Soviet-type military types like I was telling about General Cannon's visit.
But the comments I want to make, in general,
These visitors would come, and they'd go out in the field, and then, of course, they'd come back.

And before they left, most of them, I don't care really what their rank was, when they came back to leave, Ambassador Herman was interested in hearing their comments, particularly the high-level ones, you know.
They'd go to conference even.
But generally speaking, the
Visitors on these trips got the wrong impression of Russia.
No kidding.
Yes, generally speaking, I'm saying.

Now, this is discussion that Ambassador Herman a few times, and General Dean on several occasions, and I personally talk, you know, officially at meetings, and then sometimes just over coffee, you know, after dinner.
Generally speaking, they were given the wrong impression
They didn't realize that for their trip and what they saw was pre-planned to the very pencils on the table by the Russians for these visitors.
It was arranged on a basis to show the visitor what Russia wanted him to see based on what Russians
wanted to impress him with and get out of him what they wanted the most without any due regard on whatsoever of what the visitor's purpose was.
Let's say if he wanted to see how our supplies were used in Russia, that was not the Russian objective at all.
Their objective was to show him the need for more supplies and to show him maybe we weren't getting supplies.
I mean that they weren't getting supplies.
The Russians staged the whole thing.
That's a good word, staged the whole thing.
And I don't think the visitor realized this.
They'd come back and say, gee, I saw things over here.
He says, you realize what they've got over here?
Have you ever seen this?
And at times, you know, it would take us to task.
I guess they came back with a more positive approach that
this is the greatest outfit in the world and they need our help and they're doing more than you think they're doing and maybe you folks are being too negative here in the mission.
This is the general impression we got.
I distinctly remember this.
In other words, the guy that came over there and was shown a staged review of Russia left and didn't know what the hell he was
I distinctly remember when I first went to Russia, I met Air Force Colonel, Lieutenant Colonel, who I was in effect to replace.
He was out of shape.
See, we were making a bigger organization, a military mission.
And I remember meeting him on the way over in England, and he and I sat down one night just to converse with one another.
And I distinctly remember this.
I, a new man, going to Russia,

had a complete new approach you know and I was optimistic and looking forward to it and here I was talking to a very disgruntled frustrated man that was tickled to death to get out of Russia and leave his job and was fed up with the whole thing and in other words was a very negative person and I remember thinking well no wonder
were having problems dealing with the Russians.
I tried Bond to do better than this.
And in six months, I was almost the same as he was.
So this, I just mentioned this as a parallel to what I'm saying about the visitor who goes to Russia.
And in 13 months, and you left Russia, were you as negative as that lieutenant colonel?
Oh, yeah.
And...

I guess I spoke it more freely and showed it more freely than I, here I was only a colonel, I'm sure General Dean, of course he stayed there longer, but ultimately, you know, he wrote his book, The Strange Alliance, and he reflected the feelings.
I remember after six months, I was talking to my army officer, and I remember distinctly saying, Dut,
I said, we're never going to be able to do business with these people.
I said, I practically give up.
I'm through.
What did he say?
He felt the same way.
But of course, when I said I'm through, I didn't mean it that way.
And we both agreed.
But we didn't give up.
We said, we just have to keep trying our best and find ways to be more communicative with them.
it's, and I still say it, it's difficult, difficult to do business with a Russian hierarchy.
Now, were you dismissed from that job or replaced because your tour of duty was a certain time length, or did you request, how did you leave?
In effect, my tour of duty was over.
It was generally
felt that I'd be over there for about a year.
And I think, matter of fact, that's about the way General Arnold indicated, that you'd be over there about a year, never bring you back home.
And of course, one of the objectives was, since we hadn't set up the mission, is get a chance to train as many Air Force officers as possible in Russia.
And that's one way to get me back and get another colonel over there.
No.
And I admit, I was ready to come home.
This may have shown in my frustration, but I never, matter of fact, I got very good fishing reports from everybody, and Mr. Harriman hated seeing me go.
We, Mr. Harriman and I sincerely had a great mutual respect for one another.
We got along great.
What did he say to you when you left?
Did you have a meeting with him?
Well, the last time I saw him was when we landed at National Airport.
Oh, so you brought him back?
No, we came back.
I left my airplane over there.
Another crew was signed, and we came back from...
I think we came down to Cairo in my airplane and left it there.
Yeah, and then from there we rode on a C-54 type
air transport command, regular type airport, but especially chartered for him with no other passengers, just him and me and Kathy and, oh, maybe one or two other guys.
Then we landed at, eventually landed at National Airport in Washington, D.C., and that's where Chip Boland brought my wife out to meet me, and I shook hands with him, and
him and Kathy both, and I think I put one around Kathy, you know, kiss her goodbye.
We learned to know each other very well, very close.
I shook hands with the ambassador and told him how much I, it was a, not real emotional, I hated to say goodbye to him, because I liked him, and I felt he felt the same way.
He shook hands, and what a great guy, and what a grand thing you've done, Troy, and
good luck to you, you're really going to go places and all that type of stuff.
And I think that's about the last time I saw him.
I ran across him a couple of times later in my career.
A funny thing, I ran across him in Udorn, Thailand in 1967 when he was on a mission with Hubert Humphrey, a whole group of politicians, congressmen and all.
Somehow or another he got a mission to go to Vientiane, Laos.
And then he came back to Udorn to refuel
I naturally was out there to meet all of the VIPs.
All of a sudden, I saw him walking across.
He saw me about the same time.
So it was quite a reunion for a few minutes.
What did you say to him?
What did you say to him?
Oh, gee, you know, gee, Mr.
Ambassador, still Mr.
Ambassador.
Just like I, you know, left him a few days before, and great to see you and all.
He said, I didn't hear you, Charlie.
I said, what are you doing?
How do you like it and all that stuff?
And then, you know, quickly, he said, hey, come on, I want you to meet Hubert.
He took me over to introduce me to him.
Was he Vice President then or not?
Yes.
I guess so, yeah.
And he introduced me to him.
What did you think of him?
Oh, I mean, he liked him.
He was a very delightful person.
Nice.
Here he was talking to an Air Force Major General on the spot.
I liked him.
Of course, didn't know anything about him.
It was a happy meeting, you know.
He was smiling and shaking hands and all.
And the whole area just covered with senators and representatives, none of whom I even cared about meeting at that time, except, of course, Ambassador Herm.
We sat and talked a little.
I briefed, you know, generally talked about what we were doing over there and how we were doing it all.
That must have been a thrill to see him now.
Oh, yeah.
He looked older.
Yeah.
He looked older, and of course he was.
20 years older, over 25 years old.
They still had that little hunk in his back, but still had the gracious smile and the air of the diplomat about it.
Okay, are we done with Moscow?
Yeah, I think so.
How would you like to summarize that?
One of the greatest experiences I think I've ever had in my life.
It no doubt had an impact on my feelings about the world situation that probably are primary to all of my basic philosophy about many things in the world.
Economic, political, military, particularly military.
philosophical, if you will, generally speaking, psychologically.
I guess it's basic to a lot of my thinking about many of the problems in the world.
There's no doubt in my mind about what has happened interdependence-wise between nations.
I learned this in subsequent ten years working with TI, the Worldwide Selling of Munitions and Armament, a multinational corporation sitting in management meetings.
In particular, the current communications capability and air transport operations in the nation, no longer can one nation live by itself.
There's got to be interdependence.
Allah, for instance, now we're getting in bed with China.
Great.
You know, it's inevitable.
But what about Russia?
You see, there's, why not?
Well, why not?
It's obvious.
It's the ideology of communism.
I feel very strongly about this.
Why do you think that the communist Chinese can improve relations with us and seem to get along with us a little bit better, and why can't the communist Russians?
Well, I ask rhetorically.
What's the difference in Chinese communism versus Russian so-called communism?
China has an objective.
They really fear...
hate Russia at the same time.
They have reason to get in bed with us.
They don't have the armed might that the Russians have.
They have reason to get in bed with us.
I predicted in a file paper I wrote for TI when I left that we will sell arms and arm China.
And I wrote that in 1975.
People looked at me and doubted me.
We're just before doing it right now.
I kind of agree with China that it's inevitable those two thieves will eventually fight one another.
And if they do, it's got to be worldwide.
There's no way that those two would start fighting one another, and it would not spread worldwide.
OK, let's go to your next assignment.
You had two short questions.
Not short, but you had one short assignment, October 1944 to January 1945, when you came back in Washington, D.C., and this looks like a Pentagon.
Oh, yeah.
Tell me about this.
What was your title?
Briefly, I think they put me in the...
I think they put me in a training division under operations and training and determining what to do with me with my Russian experience in intelligence.
They wanted to keep me there for a while.
I think I spent really most of the time just going around briefing key generals on my experiences in Moscow and giving them impressions of my feelings about the Russian combat capability.
And then I
I think after that, I began to get, you know, look, I'm wasting my time, give me a job.
You were in the special study group there.
So then in January 1945, we remained all of 1945 in the operations of the Second Air Force in Colorado.
Where was that in Colorado?
Well, like I say, I got to
feeling I wasn't doing anything, and of course the Pentagon, it's frustrating doing it itself, and I finally talked them into letting me go out to 2nd Air Force.

2nd Air Force of Colorado Springs, and it was an organization oriented primarily to the training and converting of B-17 crews into B-29 crews, and reintroducing our effort in strategic bombing to the bigger ship, and also to Far East Japan, versus the European war, which we knew was lying down.
Did you at this time, you had not been in combat.
Now, you'd been flying, of course, all the time, but you hadn't been in combat since 1941, and here it is 1945.
Are you eager to get back in combat?
Well, that's one of the reasons.
I mean, 1942.
So 1942 is the last time you were in combat, not 1941.
So are you eager to get back in combat?
Yes, that's one of the reasons I want to go to Colorado, because part of it has a 72nd Fighter Wing under it,
And there was hardly anybody on the so-called bomber-oriented staff of Second Air Force, if you will.
And General R.B.

Williams was commander of Second Air Force at that time, and he was one of the original B-17 lieutenants in the second bomb group when I went to Langley Field on my first site where I first met him, and we grew very close.
And he knew me personally with my bomber experience.
And, of course, he'd heard about me in the Flying Tigers.
So he was delighted to get me, and he made me the assistant D.O.
under Brooke Allen, who was oriented primarily to bombers.
So he brought some fighter experience into his headquarters.
because he had the 72nd Fighter Wing under him, and we were training fighter crews.
So he was glad to get me, and I was delighted, of course.
So I looked forward to that, and that's one reason I went out there.
And I had ideas of, well, I'll get back into the fighter business now, and then I'll get me another gun and go back overseas.
And fight the Japanese again.
Right.
But I wasn't sure how long that Japanese war was going to last.
Nobody was.
Okay, how successful was the training and the shift over to the B-29?
I oriented my efforts primarily to fighters.
Okay, and what fighters were you training?
What airplane?
It was the, well it had the primarily orienting the guys to the P-51 and the P-47.
And I think they still had a few old P-40 units that had to convert.
We were training combat crews.
That's what we were doing for replacement pilots.
And fighter gunnery was one of the main things that I started pushing.
And I think we developed a fighter gunnery base in Matagorda Island, which I was very happy about because I remember, back in my experience, I hadn't been trained in fighter gunnery.
And I needed it.
And I wanted to be sure that the modern Pollock that we were putting out had fighter gunnery.
We turned out to be, we have better fighter gunnery records than the 3rd Air Force, which was the other fighter train base in Florida.
I was happy about that.
And it got along well.
So you improved their accuracy at that time.
Oh, yeah.
And their capability to shoot down fighters.
How'd you do that?
How'd you train them to be gunners?

Well, in actual missions where they would fly against fighter sleeves drawn with another aircraft down at Matagorda Island, the gunnery range, you know, way north of the coast, a plane would pull a sleeve, and then they'd make a fighter pass it at the sleeve and actually bring the sleeve back down and count the holes in it.
And, of course, we improved the equipment we had in the airplane.
We had range
automatic range setters in the aiming mechanism for the aircraft.
Did you have radar by now in these airplanes?
No, not at that time.
How were the radio systems?
You were complaining about the radios before.
Well, see that was the AVG airplanes.
We had the radios in aircraft were fine.

Matter of fact, P-50, I was ticked, I flew, I checked out and flew an early P-51 called the A-37, and I'd visit a place where we still had some of the old P-40s, and the guy, the fighter boys were tickled to death to see my airplane because it looked to them like a P-51.
I enjoyed that, that was a good tour.
And you were with your wife and family?
Let me see.
What after that?
Well, let me ask you.
Of course, you were there when the war ended in Europe in May of 1945, and again when the war ended in the Pacific in August and September of 1945.
What were your feelings then?
By the way, isn't that the same year that Roosevelt died?
Yes.
Yeah.
I remember that.
Roosevelt died April 12th.
Let me tell you about that.
We were in a staff meeting in 2nd Air Force Headquarters.
Just a daily staff meeting.

I forget what day it was, but I remember we were about ready to break up, and here come crashing through the door one of Brooke Allen's aides or some captain and so forth, and his hand is teletyped to Brooke Allen.
His comments, oh, no, Jesus, a song.
He said, the president died.
God, we all were just spelled, just struck, astounded.
And then we looked at the wire and all, and just announced the death of the president.
And we were just dumbfounded.
I never will forget that.
It's one of those times in your life, you know, that you're just something really strikes you and hits you.
And I never will forget that.
What were the feelings on base?
Oh, just terrible regret and remorse and, Lord, how we pick up and continue with this thing, you know.
It was really a shocker.
A month after that, Germany was defeated.
And do you remember your feelings finally when they signed this render?
No, I don't remember.
I think it was sort of a foregone fact that we didn't know.
What about the atomic bomb?
That now was another deal that we were amazed at.
And critically, I had no idea of such a thing at the time.
So, and you might say that was the opposite feeling about when Roosevelt died.
Goodness, boy, we ain't no, this thing, the Japanese gotta give up.
And, well this was something new, and you know, like me, something I never heard of before.
Well, who did hear of it before?
You know, you can change the course of physics, but again,
Boy, we've got it now.
This thing will be over.
Relief, pride.
Of course, later on, many people, Americans, were upset that we'd used this weapon on other humans.
What were your feelings?
I had no feeling like that whatsoever.
No telling how many American boys
this saved, no telling how many.
I have no regret whatsoever to this review.
Plus the fact that I think, as a matter of fact, there was some pluses for it.
Look what we learned from this.
Look how devastating this can be.
No wonder I feel that there's just no person in his right mind can start a nuclear war.
Nobody can win it.
It's just unthinkable.
And lo and behold, here now you begin to hear both the other side and our side think that maybe there is a thinkable nuclear war.

And you know, I know a little bit about the development of the small nukes, tactical nukes and so forth, but once that starts, I've been in exercises where I commanded the Air Force components in an exercise, Desert Strike, for instance, which was laid on for the express purpose of
starting a conventional war and having the capability of my fighters with nuclear bombs on them to try to experiment with two forces fighting one another and how would it escalate into a nuclear war.
And it took about 24 hours for it to escalate, where we started using a nuclear bomb.
Of course, we had guys playing as the president, you know, and the civilian forces above.
But again, the dropping of that bomb, boy, I don't criticize Truman one bit.
I don't criticize him one bit.
We are finally done with war in September of 1945.
What were your feelings toward a future career in the military?
Did you ever consider maybe
You'd want to get out of the military.
You still were a reserve officer, or did you want to stay in, or just what were your feelings?
Well, by this time, not that time, I was still a reserve officer.
I was a reserve colonel.
No, I was a dedicated career officer.
I didn't even think about getting out of the service.
I just wondered, my thoughts, well, what it be now.
We'll shrink our Air Force and there'll be a lot of people getting out and we'll be pulling people back home and we'll be closing bases.
Where will I go?
What do I want to do?
What job do I want?
And are we going to close up this thing too fast?
What are you going to do?
So, I had no feeling about getting out of the service at all.
It didn't sound like you were very bright though about your future.
No, I began to think, you know, well,
Now, we're going to reduce the forces also, and probably the number of generals required would be less, and I began to wonder, well, would I be promoted?
And what job would be good for the purpose of my career?
And I began to think about that.
But I still wanted to be in the Air Force.
I loved it.
Okay.
So you left in December 1945, Colorado, and then from January 1946 to December 1946, you went to Washington, D.C., headquarters of the Army Air Forces.
Tell me about that.
Was that to what you call?
Oh, yeah.
General Caldwell.
What was your title, Darryl?
I was head of the training branch.
Oh, I remember, yeah, the first thing that hit me up there was we had just begun to, we got the first P-80s, the jet aircraft, and it organized a group of them and
I recall now that's one job I loved ahead, but I didn't have a chance to, I just didn't get that job to get checked out in the P-80 and take over that first group.
But now in the training branch, I've got to think about, well, how are we going to train people to fly this airplane?
I've got to think of my training days down in Florida in AFSAT, you know, Air Force Group Flight Attack.
So I have made it to go to paper that we've got to start a jet flying school someplace.
And that's what generated the first jet flying school someplace in Texas out there.
But we got airplanes committed to that base for jet flying.
And of course, it was what we called a T-Bird, T-33.
But the first P-80s, there was a squadron

were allocated to a squad, and I forget where it was, but I remember Bruce Holloway being in on that deal, and then they were taking these airplanes, you know, they took them to Europe, to show them to people.
In other words, the Air Force was upgrading itself to jet aircraft.
This was a new age.
Oh, yeah, I bet you were excited about that.
Oh, yes, and that's, at least I was in on the training part of it.
Yeah.
So I was instrumental in getting the first training base set up for jet aircraft.
Did you ever get to fly one?
Subsequently, I did, yeah.
But you wanted, you would have liked to command that first.
Oh, goodness, everybody in the Air Force did.
I bet.
So there's a lot of competition there for that job.
Oh, yeah.

You know, there were guys in the Air Force that had many more victories than I. I was one of the biggest aces, and some of them are still fresh off a combat, you know, and like you say, I hadn't been flying
I hadn't even been flying combat aircraft since 42.
So I felt a little bit unqualified to raise my hand and say, I want that job.
But I got a lot of satisfaction out of it.
At least in the Pentagon, to get something generated and done, and then sit back and say, you know that you've done it?
Boy, that's something, the Pentagon.
Was it hectic in the Pentagon?
These were, this was the big year of demobilization, 1946.
Everybody, we went from 12 million man armed forces down to a million and a half in a year and a half, from 45 to 47.
It's wrecked.
Terrific military machine.
It's wrecked.
But rightfully so, I guess, at that time.
So was it hectic in the Pentagon?
Was it hectic in the Pentagon?
Well, yes, but not at the tense.
pace that we had during the war.
You didn't have the urgency of everything.
At least we began to relax a little.
It wasn't as frustrating and hectic as usual.
Probably a little bit more enjoyable than usual.
And what would you consider your accomplishment during that year, getting this training base set up?
than Ed Vance's typical boring staff job.
I think that's when, yes, that's when I began to, the Air University
The birth of the Air University was just about to happen.
Air War College?
Air War College.
And schooling and education began to... We had a branch in the train division called that.
And that's where I began, you know, in staff meetings, I'd listen to them talk about, well, we've got to do this, do that.
And then out of that blossomed, you know, education and training.
And the Air Force Institute of Technology, where we want Air Force officers to be, all of them to have college degrees.
And then that old urgency came up again, I remember now distinctly.
Gee, maybe I'll get in on this program and get my degree.
And that's where, really, the basic, being right in the Pentagon, fortunately, I was right at the source of the organization of the program for allowing officers, promptly qualified and deserving,
to go to a college of their own choice for at least two years towards getting a degree.
And that's how I got into the program to go to Texas A&M.
